body:
The following example reduced from UVM tests/70regs/20maps/90Mantis/5446 fails

The problem is the foreach's iterator is moving to the next element but the position has changed due to the delete/erase of the current iterator position.

My reading of IEEE 1800 12.7.3 is this is illegal "If the dimensions of a dynamically sized array are changed while iterating over a foreach-loop construct, the results are undefined and may cause invalid index values to be generated.

However every other simulator I tried this worked OK on so we should fix it.

I think fix is to have a bool init to 1 at the loop body start, clear if any delete, then use that to decide if next() increments or not.

<details>
<summary>Example</summary>

```
// verilog_format: off
`define stop $stop
`define checkd(gotv,expv) do if ((gotv) !== (expv)) begin $write("%%Error: %s:%0d:  got=%0d exp=%0d (%s !== %s)\n", `__FILE__,`__LINE__, (gotv), (expv), `"gotv`", `"e$
`ifdef verilator
 `define no_optimize(v) $c(v)
`else
 `define no_optimize(v) (v)
`endif
// verilog_format: on

module t;
  int map[int];
  int cnt;
  int q[$];

  initial begin
    map = '{0: `no_optimize(3), 1: 3, 2: 4};
    `checkd(map.size(), 3);
    cnt = 0;
    foreach (map[idx]) begin
      if (map[idx] == 3) begin
        cnt++;
        map.delete(idx);
      end
    end
    `checkd(map.size(), 1);
    `checkd(cnt, 2);

    q = '{`no_optimize(3), `no_optimize(3), `no_optimize(4)};
    `checkd(q.size(), 3);
    cnt = 0;
    foreach (q[idx]) begin
      if (q[idx] == 3) begin
        cnt++;
        q.delete(idx);
      end
    end
    `checkd(q.size(), 1);
    `checkd(cnt, 2);

    $finish;
  end
endmodule
```
</details>

